'use strict';

/* ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   MOSAIK — pixel-art picture excavation puzzle

   Each level is a real (procedurally-drawn) pixel-art picture: a grid of
   colored cells, at least a few hundred CSS pixels on screen, more
   detailed at higher levels. You don't tap individual pixels — you pick a
   color ("place a container"), and every currently-REACHABLE pixel of
   that color falls into the container in one action. Reachable = the
   bottom `bandHeight` rows of the picture (a level-scaled band, 5-10 rows)
   — as material gets extracted from the bottom, the rest of the picture
   sinks down under gravity, continuously exposing more of every color to
   the band. Win when the whole picture is cleared, within a fixed number
   of container placements ("moves").

   Columns are represented as an array of bottom-up color stacks, ALWAYS
   the same length as the grid's column count — unlike a same-color-match
   puzzle, a column that empties out must stay at its own fixed index
   (never dropped/shifted), or the picture's horizontal structure would be
   destroyed as it's cleared. "Reachable" only ever means "bottom
   bandHeight cells of each column's current stack" (or the whole column
   if shorter) — this naturally stays anchored to the visual bottom because
   gravity always keeps material bottom-packed, no absolute-row
   bookkeeping needed.

   Why generation needs no combinatorial solver (unlike Water Sort/
   Parkplatz): a color tap never makes the picture harder to finish — it
   only removes material, and gravity guarantees every remaining color
   eventually sinks into the reachable band regardless of tap order. There
   is no way to "lose" via a bad choice, no blocking, no deadlock; the only
   failure mode is running out of placements. So "solvable" isn't a search
   question — one concrete, replayable greedy playthrough (always tap
   whichever color currently has the most reachable pixels) is a complete
   proof of achievability, exactly like Parkplatz's constructive witness.
   scripts/generate-mosaik-levels.js measures that playthrough's tap count
   and sets the move budget with slack over it; scripts/verify-mosaik-
   levels.js independently re-runs the same simulation against the real
   shipped functions here before a level ships.

   Move budget / extra-moves-via-question mechanic is unchanged from the
   previous version of this game (mirrors Water Sort's extra-bottle /
   Parkplatz's extra-bay mechanic): answering a quiz question via the
   shared askQuestions() grants +1 allowed placement, capped at
   MS_MAX_EXTRA_MOVES, feeding the Tamagotchi for free like every other
   question-spending flow in this app.

   Levels are static data (MS_LEVELS below), generated offline. Only the
   shuffled play order/position and the LIVE in-progress columns/move
   state are persisted in the save; level layouts ship with the app.
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

